CAPE TOWN Advtech said on Monday it had acquired a 51 percent stake in the University of Africa (UoA), a private distance-learning university in Zambia, its first tertiary partnership outside of South Africa.The private education group said in a statement that the deal came after the International Finance Corporation invested in the group in 2016 to support its expansion strategy.Advtech said UoA had a rapidly growing student base from across the continent and an expanding portfolio of qualifications. The university had more than 2,000 students and offered 22 bachelors, eight masters and a doctoral degree. The staff complement of 145 academic and administrative employees is expected to grow rapidly as operations expand , it added.Advtech said UoA, which was founded in 2006, had established a strong brand as a leading distance education provider and has been acknowledged for its role in providing access to quality higher education in rural communities .Students live in various African countries, including Zambia, Zimbabwe, Uganda, the DRC and Swaziland.Advtech said its tertiary division would now comprise 10 brands across 26 sites in sub-Saharan Africa.Advtech s Independent Institute of Education (IIE), which is responsible for ensuring academic excellence at the group s tertiary brands, would help to benchmark the UoA s degree and diploma programmes against international best practice, the statement added. It would also advise on appointments of lecturers and academics, help develop curricula and assist with teaching and delivery methods in line with global advancements.Advtech is the holding company of the IIE, which through its brands, including Vega School of Brand Leadership, Rosebank College, Varsity College and The Design School of Southern Africa offers more than 90 qualifications, from higher certificates to post-graduate degrees.Africa News Agency